I think it's fine to cut across the grass when you have an urgent situation, and when you're just out for a stroll in the park. So the destination didn't make a huge difference for me. I think anyone can walk anywhere in a public park. The only problem that might arise is when people start to create paths that destroy the grass. But a well-designed park will have paths that people want to follow to minimize damage to the grass. Then there is the question of defining \"moral acceptability.\" I don't know that walking on the grass or the path is a moral decision one way or another. So, since I think public places are for enjoying, I could have answered \"morally neutral\" on all the maps because I don't think it's morally right or wrong to walk on the grass in a park.
